'''Envirofit International''' is a social enterprise established in 2003 to develop technology that will reduce pollution and enhance energy efficiency in developing countries.<ref>{{cite web|title=Distribution of clean cooking technology through a partnership in Kenya|url=http://www.businesscalltoaction.org/members/2013/11/envirofit-international/|publisher=Business Call to Action}}</ref> Envirofit’s founders are Tim Bauer, Nathan Lorenz, Paul Hudnut, and Bryan Willson. The social enterprise is based in Fort Collins, Colorado and has been recognized for the global impact of its innovative technology and market-based delivery of the clean energy cook stoves which help to reduce air pollution.<ref>{{cite web|title=Economist names Envirofit founders innovators of year |url=http://www.denverijournal.com/article.php?id=10015 |publisher=Denver Journal |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212073208/http://www.denverijournal.com/article.php?id=10015 |archivedate=2013-12-12 |df= }}</ref>

==History==

Envirofit International began in 2003 as an adjunct program to the Colorado State University Engines and Energy Conversion Laboratory to bring sustainable clean energy solutions to solve health and energy challenges on a global level. The first product was a retrofit technology to reduce pollution from two-stroke cycle vehicle engines in the Philippines. This project won the Rolex Award for Enterprise in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Retrofitting for the Environment|url=http://www.rolexawards.com/profiles/laureates/tim_bauer/project|publisher=Rolex Awards for Enterprise}}</ref> Envirofit engineers then turned their focus to stoves. Envirofit International’s first commercial clean cook stove model was produced in India in 2008. In order to meet the demands of consumers throughout the various markets and the growing health concerns of cooking on a traditional stove, Envirofit started to scale the model in 2010. In 2009, Nathan Lorenz and Tim Bauer were named Heroes of the Environment for their smokeless and less hazardous stove by Time Magazine.<ref>{{cite news|title=Heroes of the Environment 2009|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1924149_1924154_1924431,00.html|publisher=Times Magazine | date=22 September 2009}}</ref>

In 2007 Envirofit partnered with The Shell Foundation’s Breathing Space Program to develop clean cook stoves.<ref>{{cite web|title=Breathing Space|url=http://www.shellfoundation.org/pages/core_lines.php?p=corelines_content&page=breathing|publisher=The Shell Foundation}}</ref>

==Clean Cook Stoves==

Envirofit International developed the clean burning cook stove to help with indoor air pollution in developing countries. The design was created after engineers studied the flow of heat and smoke in a combustion chamber using computer modeling to determine the best size and shape for the stove. It was found that sheet metal can burn through in a matter of weeks. Therefore, researchers worked to develop a metal and insulation to withstand high temperatures and frequent use at a low cost. The design of the cook stove had to best fit with the consumers using it. Most of the consumers live on $2 to $10 a day and spend several hours preparing food and water for their families to use.<ref>{{cite news|last=Yee|first=Amy|title=A Healthier, More Efficient Way to Cook|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/30/business/energy-environment/30iht-rencook.html?_r=1&|publisher=The New York Times|date=29 September 2010}}</ref>

The technology of the clean cook stove has been dubbed the rocket stove because of the simple yet effective design. The cook stove has a large vertical cylinder that holds a pot and an opening at the bottom to feed the combustible biomass to cook a meal or pasteurize drinking water. In the next five years the clean stoves could reduce carbon dioxide emissions by more than 400,000 tons and prevent more than 85,000 kilograms of black carbon from entering the atmosphere. The combustion chamber of the Envirofit stoves use up to 60% less fuel than other stoves or open fires to reduce toxic emissions by up to 80%.<ref>{{cite web|title=Innovations in Air|url=http://www.uniteforsight.org/environmental-health/module12|publisher=Unite for Sight}}</ref>  There are several types of clean stoves produced by Envirofit International including the CH-4400 charcoal stove, the CH-5200 charcoal stove, the CH-2200 charcoal stove, the Z-3000 Built-In wood stove, the G-3300 wood stove, and the M-500.<ref>{{cite web|title=Improved Cook Stoves|url=http://arti-africa.org/2010/07/cook-stoves/|publisher=ARTIEnergy}}</ref>

